On a second thought this is not a good check.. The prologue directives are marked as expression statement with string literal as the text so we need test which with this change will fail:

```ts
////"use strict";
////[|function b() {
////    return this;
////}|]
////"something that should not be copied to new file";
////b();
```
You would want something like to get statements to move to get start index keeping original condition
```
const index = findIndex(statements, statement => !isPrologueDirective(statement));
```

I used `takeWhile` instead of filter to copy only prologue directives from a top of a file and ignore other, similar to the following `find*`.

https://github.com/microsoft/TypeScript/blob/ea842c411e190b306bad7c7e0aefe61ab67da7c8/src/compiler/factory/utilities.ts#L332-L344

The following test

```ts
////"use strict";
////[|function b() {
////    return this;
////}|]
////"something that should not be copied to new file";
////b();
```

The new file will look like so

```ts
////"use strict";
////export function b() {
////    return this;
////}
```

or 

https://github.com/microsoft/TypeScript/blob/8cc90b723383d4e8f828f6e555a6420d29f772df/tests/cases/fourslash/moveToNewFile_prologueDirectives6.ts#L1-L38

